The '''Greenville Grrrowl''' were an [[ECHL]] hockey team located in [[Greenville, South Carolina]]. They played their home games at the [[Bi-Lo Center|BI-LO Center]]. In the 2001-02 season, they won the [[Kelly Cup]].<ref name="fold2">{{cite web
| url=http://www.greenvilleonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20060711/NEWS01/607110332&SearchID=73250434894107
| title=Grrrowl fold; arena expected to lose money without team
| accessdate=2006-09-03
| author=Dykes, Davis
| date=2006-07-12
| work=The Greenville News}}</ref>

The Grrrowl's initial season was 1998-99, with former [[Chicago Blackhawks]] defensive star John Marks as their coach. He remained their only coach from 1998 to 2006<ref>Grrrowl.com, [http://www.grrrowl.com/team/ops/?id=598 Head Coach: John Marks]</ref>. They were an [[American Hockey League|AHL]] affiliate of the [[Norfolk Admirals]], <ref>ChicagoBlackhawks.com, [http://www.chicagoblackhawks.com/news/news.asp?story_id=3388 Hawks, Admirals Announce Affiliation w/ Toledo After Greenville Grrrowl Folds]</ref> and an [[NHL]] affiliate of the Chicago Blackhawks and the [[Edmonton Oilers]].<ref name="fold2" />

The team announced that they were folding on June 2, 2006, after running a [[United States dollar|US$]]1,000,000 deficit during 2005 that left the team unable to attract new investors.<ref name="fold3">{{cite web
| url=http://greenvilleonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20060523/NEWS01/60523011/1004/rss01
| title=Grrrowl not paying some bills, president says
| accessdate=2006-09-03
| author=Szobody, Ben and Dykes, Davis
| date=2006-05-23
| work=The Greenville News}}</ref> They began losing money after attendance slid from 7,000 per game in their first season to just 2,100 in 2004-05.<ref name="fold2" />
On June 15 the [[BI-LO Center]] announced they were willing to pay $350,000 to keep the team afloat, hoping to entice developers to save the team.<ref name="fold">{{cite web
| url=http://greenvilleonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20060615/NEWS01/606150318/1004/rss01
| title=Bi-Lo Center may pitch in for Grrrowl
| accessdate=2006-09-03
| author=Szobody, Ben
| date=2006-06-15
| work=The Greenville News}}</ref> Despite the offer, the Greenville Grrrowl ceased operation on July 10, 2006 when the team failed to find new sources of financing.<ref name="fold2" /> According to Grrrowl President Ed Rubinstein, the team only plans to refund "some percentage" of money already paid by season ticket holders.<ref name="fold2" />

== Retired Numbers ==
*''#36'' <U+2013> When Nick Vitucci retired in 2004. Nick played in 14 ECHL Seasons, his last 3 with the Greenville Grrrowl. He is now a head coach for the [[Toledo Storm]]<ref>ToledoStorm.com, [http://www.toledostorm.com/content.php?page=staff.php&token=1 Front Office Staff]</ref>.

